# TypeScript testing

Pair with `../general/tdd.md` (the cycle and the four pillars) and
`../general/testing.md` (where each kind of test lives).

## Runner: Vitest

[Vitest](https://vitest.dev/) is the default test runner — Vite-native,
TS-first, Jest-compatible API.

```sh
npm test                    # run once
npm run test:watch          # watch mode (TDD loop)
npm test -- order           # filter by name
npm test -- --coverage      # with coverage
```

If the project uses Jest instead, the API is mostly identical
(`describe`, `it`, `expect`); the rest of this document applies the
same.

## Test layout

```
src/
├── domain/
│   ├── order.ts
│   └── order.test.ts        ← co-located unit test
└── application/
    └── placeOrder.ts
tests/
├── integration/
│   └── orders.api.test.ts   ← cross-module + real adapters
└── e2e/
    └── checkout.test.ts     ← through the public HTTP/CLI boundary
```

- **Unit tests live next to source files** (`*.test.ts` /
  `*.spec.ts`). Co-location keeps related code visible.
- `tests/integration/` and `tests/e2e/` for tests that exercise
  multiple modules or hit real I/O.

Configure include patterns in `vitest.config.ts` accordingly.

## Anatomy of a test

```ts
import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";

describe("Order.refund", () => {
  it("marks a paid order as refunded", () => {
    // Arrange
    const order = Order.placed(items, money(100, "USD"));
    order.markPaid();

    // Act
    order.refund("customer requested");

    // Assert
    expect(order.status).toBe("refunded");
    expect(order.refundedAt).toBeInstanceOf(Date);
  });
});
```

- Three phases — Arrange / Act / Assert — separated by blank lines.
- One state-changing call in Act.
- One logical outcome in Assert; multiple `expect`s checking facets
  of it are fine.

## Naming

`it("<does what> when <condition>")` — read it as a sentence:

- `it("normalises an email to lowercase")`
- `it("rejects a refund when the order is unpaid")`
- `it("returns an empty page when offset is past the end")`

`describe` blocks group by unit under test, not by category. Nest
sparingly; one or two levels.

## Fixtures and factories

Vitest doesn't have pytest-style fixtures; use plain functions.

```ts
function aPaidOrder(): Order {
  const o = Order.placed(items(), money(50, "USD"));
  o.markPaid();
  return o;
}
```

- Factories take optional overrides for variations:
  `aPaidOrder({ total: money(1000, "USD") })`.
- For setup/teardown, use `beforeEach` / `afterEach` (Vitest's
  Jest-compatible hooks).

## Parametrize

Vitest's `it.each`:

```ts
it.each([
  [0,   "USD", true],
  [10,  "USD", true],
  [-1,  "USD", false],
  [10,  "usd", false],
  [10,  "XX",  false],
])("money(%i, %s) valid? %s", (amount, currency, valid) => {
  if (valid) expect(() => money(amount, currency)).not.toThrow();
  else       expect(() => money(amount, currency)).toThrow();
});
```

Reach for `it.each` before reaching for property-based testing.

## Property-based testing with fast-check

```ts
import { fc, it } from "@fast-check/vitest";

it.prop([fc.integer({ min: 0, max: 1_000_000 }), fc.integer({ min: 0, max: 1_000_000 })])(
  "money addition is commutative",
  (a, b) => {
    const m1 = moneyUsd(a);
    const m2 = moneyUsd(b);
    expect(m1.add(m2)).toEqual(m2.add(m1));
  },
);
```

`fast-check` finds edge cases you wouldn't enumerate (zero, max,
weird precision). Install: `npm i -D @fast-check/vitest fast-check`.

Use on: value-object constructors, parsers, encoder/decoder pairs,
pure transformations in `domain/`.

## Mocking — classical school, sparingly

Same rule as the rest of the codebase: **mock only out-of-process
dependencies**.

- For in-process collaborators: pass a real or hand-rolled
  in-memory implementation of the interface. Don't mock.
- For HTTP / DB / queue / clock / filesystem: mock or use a fake.

```ts
class InMemoryOrderRepository implements OrderRepository {
  private readonly orders = new Map<OrderId, Order>();
  async get(id: OrderId): Promise<Order | undefined> { return this.orders.get(id); }
  async save(o: Order): Promise<void> { this.orders.set(o.id, o); }
}

it("place_order persists the order", async () => {
  const repo = new InMemoryOrderRepository();
  const useCase = new PlaceOrderUseCase(repo, fixedClock(new Date("2026-01-01")));

  const id = await useCase.execute(aPlaceOrderCommand());

  expect(await repo.get(id)).toBeDefined();
});
```

For HTTP, prefer [MSW](https://mswjs.io/) (request-level mock) over
`vi.spyOn(fetch)`.

For time, inject a `Clock` interface and use a `FakeClock` in tests;
don't rely on Vitest's `vi.useFakeTimers` for domain logic — it leaks
global state.

## Snapshots — sparingly

Snapshot tests (`toMatchSnapshot()`, `toMatchInlineSnapshot()`) are
good for complex stable outputs and dangerous when overused (every
small change becomes a snapshot update treadmill).

Rule of thumb: snapshot the *shape* you can't easily assert
field-by-field. Don't snapshot rendered HTML you haven't read.

## What to test

| Layer | Coverage style |
| --- | --- |
| `domain` | High. Every invariant, edge case, error. Pure → loves unit tests. |
| `application` | Integration tests against in-memory adapters. |
| `infrastructure` | Integration tests against the real external system in a container, or MSW for HTTP. |
| `presentation` | Small set of e2e tests through the public HTTP/CLI boundary (Playwright for browser apps). |

## What NOT to test

- Trivial property reads with no logic.
- Type-only constructs (`type X = ...`). The compiler tests them.
- Implementation details — `expect(privateHelper).toHaveBeenCalled()`
  is a refactor magnet.
- Third-party library internals — test *your usage*.

## TDD with Vitest

The full ritual (mirrors `../general/tdd.md`):

1. `npm run test:watch` — Vitest is now watching.
2. Write a failing test. Red. Confirm it fails for the right reason.
3. Write the simplest implementation that turns it green.
4. Refactor with the test as safety net.
5. Commit.
6. Update the test list. Repeat.

`npm run test:watch -- --changed` reruns only the tests whose source
files changed — great for tight TDD loops in large codebases.

## E2E with Playwright (when applicable)

For browser e2e:

```ts
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";

test("user can place an order", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("/");
  await page.fill("[name=email]", "alice@example.com");
  await page.click("button:has-text('Sign in')");
  await expect(page).toHaveURL(/dashboard/);
});
```

Keep e2e small in number; rely on lower layers for coverage. Each
e2e test costs minutes of CI; don't repeat unit-test work there.
